Most of South Africa's infections -- around two-thirds -- are found in the Western Cape province. JOHANNESBURG - South Africa's confirmed coronavirus infections have jumped by more than 10,000 in five days to 61,927 on Friday, official statistics showed. Positive cases stood at 50,879 on Monday, just a week after the continent's worst-hit country further eased lockdown restrictions. READ: Mkhize: Low-risk areas could move to lower levels soon South Africa accounts for nearly 25 percent of the continent's total cases, according to the World Health Organization. The latest figures released by the health ministry showed that the virus has so far killed 1,354 people in the country since the first case was detected in March. READ: Interventions in fight against COVID-19 are working - Makhura Most of South Africa's infections -- around two-thirds -- are found in the Western Cape province. WHO said that the pandemic was accelerating on the continent and that 10 of the 54 countries on the continent are currently driving the numbers. - Coronavirus Hotline Number: 0800 029 999 from 8am to 4pm, Monday to Friday. Help protect your loved ones by sharing this official South African government COVID-19 service with your family, friends and community. Send HI to 0600 123 456 on WhatsApp. The NICD has another Clinician Hotline to improve #COVID19 communication and support for healthcare providers. The Clinician Hotline is 0800 11 1131, operating 24 hrs. The Public Hotline is 0800 029 999 also operating 24hrs.